"{\"content\":{\"body\":\"**ENS (Ethereum Name Service)**\\n\\n![](https://images.mirror-media.xyz/publication-images/awcx73ZKUWBio_oyo8YMY.png?height=644&width=1440)\\n\\n“The Ethereum Name Service (ENS) is a distributed, open, and extensible naming system based on the Ethereum blockchain”. This translates to human readable names (such as Michael.eth) that connect to Ethereum addresses, making it far easier to use (and remember your address). \\n\\nPractically, this allows people to send and receive crypto in a similar way to direct messaging someone on Twitter or Instagram, or searching google.com. Recently, ENS launched a DAO and [governance token](https://ens.mirror.xyz/-eaqMv7XPikvXhvjbjzzPNLS4wzcQ8vdOgi9eNXeUuY), decentralizing themselves and putting voting power in the hands of the community. This was a large airdrop to users of .eth domains, and helps push accessibility to crypto to more users. \\n\\n![Registering your .eth domain](https://images.mirror-media.xyz/publication-images/7MmFgecCnSgTS0CCmwOr2.png?height=798&width=1362)\\n\\n**Quick glossary** \\n\\n*Name*: An ENS identifier such as 'alice.eth'. Names may consist of multiple parts, called labels, separated by dots.\\n\\n*Controller*: The account that may edit the records of a name. The Controller may be changed by the Registrant or Controller.\\n\\n*Registrar*: A registrar is a contract responsible for allocating subdomains. Registrars can be configured at any level of ENS, and are pointed to by the owner field of the registry.\\n\\n*Registrant*: The owner of a registration. The registrant may transfer the registration, set the Controller, and reclaim ownership of the name in the registry if required.** \\n  \\n Etherscan**\\n\\n[Etherscan](https://etherscan.io/) is one of the most underrated and powerful tools on Ethereum. It acts as a blockchain explorer (or search engine) to better read the Ethereum blockchain.\\n\\n![](https://images.mirror-media.xyz/publication-images/XsZrkoj1plvULOmFv36Ak.png?height=1118&width=1708)\\n\\nUsing Etherscan, you can see what actions a given Ethereum address (Or ENS name!) is doing, such as buying, selling, or transacting. Advanced users watch certain addresses for creation of new contracts (that could be a hot new project launch by Andre Cronje) or for selling movements by large groups (such as the Ethereum foundation) to gain alpha. \\n\\nCheck out Eth Hub’s great [explainer](https://docs.ethhub.io/guides/deciphering-a-transaction-on-etherscan/) on Etherscan, and try playing around with different tabs in Etherscan. Start by looking up your own address!\",\"timestamp\":1638479449,\"title\":\"Michael's Musings #3 (ENS and Etherscan)\"},\"digest\":\"SSNUZHOmV0OfizPopGFYPC5NazSIVGrCT7CG9vqQSw8\",\"authorship\":{\"contributor\":\"0xA10140C60dB1ed67a5d70252B6b9B4C9904458B8\",\"signingKey\":\"{\\\"crv\\\":\\\"P-256\\\",\\\"ext\\\":true,\\\"key_ops\\\":[\\\"verify\\\"],\\\"kty\\\":\\\"EC\\\",\\\"x\\\":\\\"g5x2vZweNfsh8UGsDxFJ1VGXpHQlpAdx7dgK_OSmQqY\\\",\\\"y\\\":\\\"ZskQFAReUX7LuBBiP_PUtLCnYE-exNUYAHaLjVHcPKQ\\\"}\",\"signature\":\"Wy8urPEr1kl17G2W2iphszU4lSTciM4VMUnqNWkeslf7k7dkROLZPTLTDAxcGRIUyqW0xNlcKRII6kjSG4WqTA\",\"signingKeySignature\":\"0x7eac0d620f871c3d4294e3766fee5fb07e35ce334d3aa78814d98cc4bdc1bdf40d4289a18b069c39135234fe6ef20abc8e270a1c28a675bca78ac9001886aea81c\",\"signingKeyMessage\":\"I authorize publishing on mirror.xyz from this device using:\\n{\\\"crv\\\":\\\"P-256\\\",\\\"ext\\\":true,\\\"key_ops\\\":[\\\"verify\\\"],\\\"kty\\\":\\\"EC\\\",\\\"x\\\":\\\"g5x2vZweNfsh8UGsDxFJ1VGXpHQlpAdx7dgK_OSmQqY\\\",\\\"y\\\":\\\"ZskQFAReUX7LuBBiP_PUtLCnYE-exNUYAHaLjVHcPKQ\\\"}\",\"algorithm\":{\"name\":\"ECDSA\",\"hash\":\"SHA-256\"}},\"nft\":{},\"version\":\"12-21-2020\",\"originalDigest\":\"SSNUZHOmV0OfizPopGFYPC5NazSIVGrCT7CG9vqQSw8\"}"